## Question a ##
timeseries <- ts(Datadow$Closing.Values, frequency = 1, start = 1)
Growth_Factor <- timeseries/stats::lag(timeseries, - 1)
Geometric_Mean_Rate <- round(100*(geometric.mean(Growth_Factor)-1), digits = 2)
Geometric_Mean_Rate
## [1] 0.6
sprintf("Dow's average return rate is %.2f.", Geometric_Mean_Rate)
## [1] "Dow's average return rate is 0.60."
Return <-c(NA, Growth_Factor)
dfrev <- data.frame(Datadow$Month, Return)
## Question b ##
hist(dfrev$Return)

sprintf("The histogram shown has a bell shape, therefore it's normally distributed.")
## [1] "The histogram shown has a bell shape, therefore it's normally distributed."
## Question c ##
stddev <- sd(dfrev$Return, na.rm=TRUE)
sprintf("The std dev of proportion of Closing values revenue is %.2f.", stddev)
## [1] "The std dev of proportion of Closing values revenue is 0.04."
TotalSampleSize <- length(dfrev$Return)
One_SD_Range_Lower <- Geometric_Mean_Rate - 1*stddev
One_SD_Range_Upper <- Geometric_Mean_Rate + 1*stddev

## Proportion of observations within 1 SD (should be around 68%)
proportionER1 <- pnorm(One_SD_Range_Upper, mean=Geometric_Mean_Rate, sd=stddev) - pnorm(One_SD_Range_Lower, mean=Geometric_Mean_Rate, sd=stddev)

Two_SD_Range_Lower <- Geometric_Mean_Rate - 2*stddev
Two_SD_Range_Upper <- Geometric_Mean_Rate + 2*stddev

## Proportion of observations within 2 SD (should be around 95%) 
proportionER2 <- pnorm(Two_SD_Range_Upper, mean=Geometric_Mean_Rate, sd=stddev) - pnorm(Two_SD_Range_Lower, mean=Geometric_Mean_Rate, sd=stddev)


Three_SD_Range_Lower <- average_datadow - 3*stddev
Three_SD_Range_Upper <- average_datadow + 3*stddev

## Proportion of observations within 2 SD (should be around 99.7%) 
proportionER3 <- pnorm(Three_SD_Range_Upper, mean=Geometric_Mean_Rate, sd=stddev) - pnorm(Three_SD_Range_Lower, mean=Geometric_Mean_Rate, sd=stddev)

sprintf("%.1f%% of the revenues are within 1SD from the mean.", proportionER1*100)
## [1] "68.3% of the revenues are within 1SD from the mean."
sprintf("%.1f%% of the revenues are within 2SD from the mean.", proportionER2*100)
## [1] "95.4% of the revenues are within 2SD from the mean."
sprintf("%.1f%% of the revenues are within 3SD from the mean.", proportionER3*100)
## [1] "0.0% of the revenues are within 3SD from the mean."

print("As it is normally distributed, both quartiles (Q1 and Q3) are approximately the same distance from the mean. The first quartile is slightly closer to the mean, meaning that values are less spread than from the mean to the third quartile. The difference is insignificant.")

## Question e ##
IQR <- IQR(dfrev$Return, na.rm = TRUE) ## IQR
sprintf("First Quartile: 25 percent of revenues are less than %.2f  and 75 percent of them are more than %.2f.", Q1, Q1)
## [1] "First Quartile: 25 percent of revenues are less than 0.98  and 75 percent of them are more than 0.98."
sprintf("Second Quartile: 50 percent of revenues are less than %.2f and 50 percent of them are more than %.2f.", Q2, Q2)
## [1] "Second Quartile: 50 percent of revenues are less than 1.01 and 50 percent of them are more than 1.01."
sprintf("Third Quartile: 75 percent of revenues are less than %.2f  and 25 percent of them are more than %.2f.", Q3, Q3)
## [1] "Third Quartile: 75 percent of revenues are less than 1.03  and 25 percent of them are more than 1.03."
sprintf("The variation in middle 50%% of revenues is %.3f.", IQR)
## [1] "The variation in middle 50% of revenues is 0.048."
Tmin = Q1-(1.5*IQR)
Tmax = Q3+(1.5*IQR)
Tminmin = Q1-(3*IQR)
Tmaxmax = Q3+(3*IQR)
sprintf("Any number smaller than %.2f and greater than %.2f is an outlier. Any number smaller than %.2f and greater than %.2f is an extreme outlier.", Tmin, Tmax, Tminmin, Tmaxmax)
## [1] "Any number smaller than 0.91 and greater than 1.11 is an outlier. Any number smaller than 0.84 and greater than 1.18 is an extreme outlier."

Furthermore, the different plots show that there is not a significant relationship between the evening and night calls/minutes and the churn, whereas it exists a relationship between the day charge and the churn: the mean of the churn is higher when the day charge is higher. Also, the proportion of users with international plan that churn is lower than the average, whereas the proportion of users with voice mail plans that churn is higher that the average. There is also a relationship between the number of calls to customer service and the churnability: the more calls to customer service, the higher the churnability. As expected, the more minutes done, the higher the charge and the higher churnability (high positive linear correlation). Surprisingly, the more calls doesn't mean a higher charge and therefore doesn't mean a higher churnability. But there is not a relationship between users who have minutes/calls during different times of the day, eliminating the theory that the same users who call/use minutes more during one time, call/use minutes more during other times too. After having observed these relationships, I'd give the company the following recommendations: 1. focus more on having a better customer service, as the relationship between customer call service and churnability may be an indicator of the customers giving notice that they are not happy with the company. 2.
